('130e8400-e29b-41d4-a716-446655440100', NULL, '300e8400-e29b-41d4-a716-446655440100', 'Reading Passage 1', 'Read the passage and answer questions 1-13', '{"reading_passage": {"title": "The History of Human Migration", "content": "The history of human migration is a fascinating subject that spans thousands of years and encompasses the movement of people across continents, oceans, and cultures. Early humans began migrating from Africa approximately 60,000 years ago, gradually populating different continents through a series of remarkable journeys that shaped the course of human civilization. This migration was driven by various factors including climate change, the search for food and resources, population pressure, and the innate human desire to explore and settle new territories. Archaeological evidence shows that these early migrations were not random but followed specific routes, often along coastlines and river valleys where resources were more abundant. Researchers have discovered that early humans possessed sophisticated navigation skills, using natural landmarks, celestial bodies, and environmental cues to guide their journeys. The migration patterns reveal a complex understanding of geography and resource management that enabled human populations to thrive in diverse environments. One of the most significant migration routes was the coastal path from Africa through the Middle East and into Asia, which allowed early humans to access marine resources and avoid harsh inland conditions. This route eventually led to the peopling of Australia and the Pacific islands, demonstrating remarkable seafaring capabilities that were previously underestimated. The discovery of ancient tools and artifacts along these routes provides crucial insights into the technological innovations that facilitated long-distance travel. The migration to the Americas represents another extraordinary chapter in human history. Scientists believe that humans crossed the Bering Land Bridge during the last Ice Age, when sea levels were lower and a land connection existed between Asia and North America. This migration required adaptation to extreme cold conditions and the development of specialized survival techniques. The subsequent spread throughout the Americas occurred over thousands of years, with different groups developing unique cultures and technologies adapted to their specific environments. Evidence from archaeological sites across North and South America shows sophisticated adaptations to local climates, from the Arctic tundra to tropical rainforests. Climate change played a crucial role in driving and enabling these migrations. Periods of warming and cooling created opportunities for movement while also presenting challenges that required adaptation. The ability to adapt to changing environmental conditions became a key factor in the success of migrating populations. This adaptability is evident in the diverse range of cultures, languages, and technologies that emerged in different regions. During the last glacial maximum, when much of the northern hemisphere was covered in ice, human populations were forced to migrate to more hospitable regions, leading to significant population movements and cultural exchanges. Modern genetic studies have revolutionized our understanding of human migration patterns. By analyzing DNA from contemporary populations and ancient remains, scientists can trace migration routes with unprecedented accuracy. These studies reveal that human populations are more interconnected than previously thought, with genetic evidence showing multiple waves of migration and interbreeding between different groups. The field of population genetics has uncovered fascinating details about how different human groups are related, showing that all modern humans share a common African ancestry while also revealing the complex web of migrations that occurred over tens of thousands of years. The impact of these migrations extends far beyond the movement of people. They facilitated the exchange of ideas, technologies, and cultural practices that shaped human development. Agricultural techniques, tool-making methods, and artistic traditions spread along migration routes, creating a rich tapestry of human innovation and creativity. The domestication of plants and animals, for instance, spread from its origins in the Fertile Crescent to other parts of the world through migration and trade networks. Similarly, metallurgical knowledge, architectural styles, and religious beliefs traveled with migrating populations, leading to the rich cultural diversity we see today. The legacy of these ancient migrations continues to influence modern societies, as evidenced by the distribution of languages, genetic markers, and cultural practices around the world. Linguistic studies have shown how language families spread with migrating populations, while archaeological evidence demonstrates the transmission of technologies and artistic styles. Understanding these historical migration patterns helps us appreciate the interconnectedness of human societies and provides valuable insights into how populations adapt to new environments and challenges.", "paragraphs": [{"id": "para-1", "label": "A", "content": "The history of human migration is a fascinating subject that spans thousands of years and encompasses the movement of people across continents, oceans, and cultures. Early humans began migrating from Africa approximately 60,000 years ago, gradually populating different continents through a series of remarkable journeys that shaped the course of human civilization. This migration was driven by various factors including climate change, the search for food and resources, population pressure, and the innate human desire to explore and settle new territories. Archaeological evidence shows that these early migrations were not random but followed specific routes, often along coastlines and river valleys where resources were more abundant."}, {"id": "para-2", "label": "B", "content": "Researchers have discovered that early humans possessed sophisticated navigation skills, using natural landmarks, celestial bodies, and environmental cues to guide their journeys. The migration patterns reveal a complex understanding of geography and resource management that enabled human populations to thrive in diverse environments. One of the most significant migration routes was the coastal path from Africa through the Middle East and into Asia, which allowed early humans to access marine resources and avoid harsh inland conditions. This route eventually led to the peopling of Australia and the Pacific islands, demonstrating remarkable seafaring capabilities that were previously underestimated. The discovery of ancient tools and artifacts along these routes provides crucial insights into the technological innovations that facilitated long-distance travel."}, {"id": "para-3", "label": "C", "content": "The migration to the Americas represents another extraordinary chapter in human history. Scientists believe that humans crossed the Bering Land Bridge during the last Ice Age, when sea levels were lower and a land connection existed between Asia and North America. This migration required adaptation to extreme cold conditions and the development of specialized survival techniques. The subsequent spread throughout the Americas occurred over thousands of years, with different groups developing unique cultures and technologies adapted to their specific environments. Evidence from archaeological sites across North and South America shows sophisticated adaptations to local climates, from the Arctic tundra to tropical rainforests."}, {"id": "para-4", "label": "D", "content": "Climate change played a crucial role in driving and enabling these migrations. Periods of warming and cooling created opportunities for movement while also presenting challenges that required adaptation. The ability to adapt to changing environmental conditions became a key factor in the success of migrating populations. This adaptability is evident in the diverse range of cultures, languages, and technologies that emerged in different regions. During the last glacial maximum, when much of the northern hemisphere was covered in ice, human populations were forced to migrate to more hospitable regions, leading to significant population movements and cultural exchanges."}, {"id": "para-5", "label": "E", "content": "Modern genetic studies have revolutionized our understanding of human migration patterns. By analyzing DNA from contemporary populations and ancient remains, scientists can trace migration routes with unprecedented accuracy. These studies reveal that human populations are more interconnected than previously thought, with genetic evidence showing multiple waves of migration and interbreeding between different groups. The field of population genetics has uncovered fascinating details about how different human groups are related, showing that all modern humans share a common African ancestry while also revealing the complex web of migrations that occurred over tens of thousands of years."}, {"id": "para-6", "label": "F", "content": "The impact of these migrations extends far beyond the movement of people. They facilitated the exchange of ideas, technologies, and cultural practices that shaped human development. Agricultural techniques, tool-making methods, and artistic traditions spread along migration routes, creating a rich tapestry of human innovation and creativity. The domestication of plants and animals, for instance, spread from its origins in the Fertile Crescent to other parts of the world through migration and trade networks. Similarly, metallurgical knowledge, architectural styles, and religious beliefs traveled with migrating populations, leading to the rich cultural diversity we see today."}, {"id": "para-7", "label": "G", "content": "The legacy of these ancient migrations continues to influence modern societies, as evidenced by the distribution of languages, genetic markers, and cultural practices around the world. Linguistic studies have shown how language families spread with migrating populations, while archaeological evidence demonstrates the transmission of technologies and artistic styles. Understanding these historical migration patterns helps us appreciate the interconnectedness of human societies and provides valuable insights into how populations adapt to new environments and challenges."}]}}', 'mock_test', 'reading', 20, 1, 0.00, 1, TRUE, NULL),
-- Passage 2: Full passage text in exercise.content (IELTS standard: 700-900 words)
('130e8400-e29b-41d4-a716-446655440101', NULL, '300e8400-e29b-41d4-a716-446655440100', 'Reading Passage 2', 'Read the passage and answer questions 14-27', '{"passage": "The Development of Modern Medicine\n\nA\n\nThe development of modern medicine has revolutionized healthcare and extended human life expectancy significantly over the past century. From the discovery of antibiotics in the early 20th century to advanced surgical techniques and medical imaging technologies, medical science has made remarkable progress in treating diseases and improving quality of life. The introduction of vaccines has virtually eliminated many deadly diseases that once claimed millions of lives annually, while surgical innovations have made previously impossible procedures routine. The average human lifespan has increased from approximately 45 years in 1900 to over 70 years in many parts of the world today, largely due to advances in medical science and public health measures.\n\nB\n\nHowever, the medical field faces numerous challenges in the 21st century. Antibiotic resistance has emerged as a critical threat, with many bacterial infections becoming increasingly difficult to treat. This problem has been exacerbated by the overuse of antibiotics in both human medicine and agriculture. The World Health Organization has identified antibiotic resistance as one of the biggest threats to global health, food security, and development today. The rising cost of healthcare has also become a significant concern, particularly in developed countries where medical expenses can be prohibitive for many individuals and families. Additionally, ensuring access to medical services in developing countries remains a major challenge, with millions of people lacking basic healthcare facilities.\n\nC\n\nThe future of medicine lies in several promising areas. Personalized treatments based on individual genetic profiles are becoming increasingly common, allowing doctors to tailor medications and therapies to specific patients. This approach, known as precision medicine, takes into account individual variability in genes, environment, and lifestyle. Gene therapy offers the potential to cure genetic disorders by correcting defective genes, while regenerative medicine aims to repair or replace damaged tissues and organs using stem cells and tissue engineering. Preventive care is also gaining importance, with greater emphasis on lifestyle modifications, early detection, and health education to prevent diseases before they develop.\n\nD\n\nTechnological innovations continue to transform medical practice. Artificial intelligence is being used to analyze medical images, assist in diagnosis, and predict patient outcomes with remarkable accuracy. Machine learning algorithms can now detect patterns in medical data that might be missed by human doctors, leading to earlier diagnosis and more effective treatments. Telemedicine has expanded access to healthcare, particularly in remote areas, while wearable devices enable continuous monitoring of health parameters such as heart rate, blood pressure, and blood glucose levels. Robotics and minimally invasive surgical techniques have reduced recovery times and improved surgical precision, allowing for procedures that were once considered impossible.\n\nE\n\nDespite these advances, ethical considerations remain paramount. Issues such as patient privacy, informed consent, and equitable access to new treatments require careful consideration. The medical community must balance innovation with responsibility, ensuring that new technologies benefit all members of society while maintaining the highest standards of care and ethical practice. The use of genetic information raises concerns about discrimination and privacy, while the high cost of new treatments creates challenges for healthcare systems worldwide. There is an ongoing debate about how to ensure that medical advances are accessible to all, regardless of socioeconomic status.\n\nF\n\nResearch in medicine continues to push boundaries, with scientists exploring new frontiers in areas such as nanotechnology, immunotherapy, and brain-computer interfaces. Nanotechnology offers the potential for targeted drug delivery and early disease detection at the molecular level. Immunotherapy has shown remarkable success in treating certain types of cancer by harnessing the body''s own immune system. Brain-computer interfaces hold promise for helping people with paralysis or neurological conditions regain function. These cutting-edge technologies represent the next wave of medical innovation, though they also bring new ethical and practical challenges that must be carefully navigated.\n\nG\n\nThe global nature of modern medicine means that diseases and health challenges are increasingly interconnected. Pandemics such as COVID-19 have demonstrated the importance of international cooperation in medical research and public health. Climate change is also emerging as a significant health threat, affecting everything from the spread of infectious diseases to food security and mental health. As medicine continues to evolve, it must address not only individual health but also population health and global health security, requiring collaboration across borders and disciplines."}', 'mock_test', 'reading', 20, 1, 0.00, 2, TRUE, NULL),
-- Passage 3: Full passage text in exercise.content (IELTS standard: 700-900 words)
('130e8400-e29b-41d4-a716-446655440102', NULL, '300e8400-e29b-41d4-a716-446655440100', 'Reading Passage 3', 'Read the passage and answer questions 28-40', '{"passage": "The Impact of Social Media on Modern Society\n\nA\n\nThe impact of social media on modern society is profound and multifaceted, transforming how people communicate, access information, and engage with the world around them. While social media platforms have connected billions of people worldwide and facilitated unprecedented information sharing, they have also raised significant concerns about privacy, mental health, and the spread of misinformation. Understanding these complex dynamics is essential for navigating the digital landscape effectively. Social media has fundamentally changed the way we interact, work, and perceive the world, creating both opportunities and challenges that previous generations never encountered.\n\nB\n\nOne of the most significant positive impacts of social media is its ability to connect people across geographical boundaries. Families separated by distance can maintain close relationships through video calls and instant messaging, sharing daily moments and important milestones in real-time. Friends can share life updates instantly, and communities can form around shared interests regardless of physical location. Social media has also democratized information access, allowing individuals to learn about events, cultures, and perspectives from around the world. Educational content, news, and cultural exchanges happen at an unprecedented scale, breaking down traditional barriers to information and understanding.\n\nC\n\nHowever, the negative consequences of social media use cannot be overlooked. Research indicates that excessive social media use can lead to anxiety, depression, and feelings of isolation, particularly among young people. The constant comparison with others'' curated online personas can create unrealistic expectations and diminish self-esteem. Studies have shown that spending more than two hours per day on social media is associated with poor mental health outcomes, including increased rates of depression and anxiety. Cyberbullying has become a serious problem, with victims experiencing psychological distress that can have long-lasting effects. The anonymity and distance provided by digital platforms can embolden harmful behavior that might not occur in face-to-face interactions.\n\nD\n\nPrivacy concerns represent another major issue. Social media platforms collect vast amounts of personal data, often without users fully understanding how this information is used. This data can be sold to advertisers, used to manipulate user behavior, or potentially accessed by unauthorized parties. The Cambridge Analytica scandal highlighted how personal data could be exploited for political purposes, raising questions about the ethical use of social media data. Users often trade their personal information for free access to platforms, creating a business model that prioritizes engagement and advertising revenue over user privacy and well-being.\n\nE\n\nThe spread of misinformation and fake news has become a critical challenge. Social media algorithms designed to maximize engagement often prioritize sensational or controversial content, regardless of its accuracy. This has contributed to the polarization of public discourse and undermined trust in traditional media and institutions. The rapid spread of false information during crises, such as the COVID-19 pandemic, has demonstrated the real-world consequences of misinformation, leading to public health risks and social unrest. Echo chambers and filter bubbles can reinforce existing beliefs while preventing exposure to diverse perspectives, further contributing to societal division.\n\nF\n\nDespite these challenges, social media can be a powerful tool when used responsibly. Educational institutions have leveraged social media to enhance learning, with teachers using platforms to share resources, facilitate discussions, and connect with students. Activists have used social media to organize movements, raise awareness about important issues, and mobilize support for causes. The Arab Spring and various social justice movements have demonstrated the power of social media to facilitate political change and social mobilization. Community building has flourished online, with groups forming around hobbies, support networks, and shared experiences, providing connection and belonging for people who might otherwise feel isolated.\n\nG\n\nThe future of social media will likely involve greater regulation and user awareness. Governments are implementing stricter data protection laws, such as the European Union''s General Data Protection Regulation, while platforms are developing tools to combat misinformation and protect user privacy. Digital literacy education is becoming increasingly important, helping users navigate social media more critically and responsibly. As society continues to adapt to this digital revolution, finding the right balance between the benefits and drawbacks of social media remains an ongoing challenge. The responsibility lies not only with platform developers and regulators but also with individual users to engage thoughtfully and ethically with these powerful communication tools."}', 'mock_test', 'reading', 20, 1, 0.00, 3, TRUE, NULL),

